    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: Raycasting from the Mouse
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "Perhaps the most common use of raycasts is for facilitating
          player input. The mouse position of the player in Unity is stored as a
          Vector2 of the X and Y positions of the mouse on the <i>screen</i> (i.e.
          in <b>screen-space</b>), and so if we want to use player input to interact
          with objects in the game world (e.g. to select items, or specify where
          to shoot or walk), then we need to convert this screen space coordinate
          into a <b>world-space</b> coordinate. Even in a 2D top-down game like the
          ones we have been developing so far, this is not always trivial, as the
          camera may have moved or rotated. In 3D or 2.5D, this is even more difficult,
          as we need to take into account depth, and the perspective projection of
          the camera in determining what was underneath the cursor when it was clicked.\r\nIn
          order to come up with a world space point from the screen space coordinates
          of the mouse, we must cast a ray from the point on the \u201Csurface\u201D
          of the camera (you can think of this as the lens), and out into the game
          world, taking into account the projection of the camera:\r"
